<section id="what-is">
      <h2>What Is the Spring Festival?</h2>
      <p>The Spring Festival (<span class="chinese-char">春節</span>, Chūnjié), also known as Chinese New Year, marks the beginning of a new year on the traditional <a href="/calendar/">Chinese lunisolar calendar</a>. It is the most important festival in Chinese culture, celebrated for at least 3,500 years, and the longest public holiday in China and many East Asian nations.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="origins">
      <h2>Ancient Origins</h2>
      <p>The festival's roots lie in ancient year-end sacrificial rites (<span class="chinese-char">臘祭</span>, làjì) during the Shang Dynasty, when people offered sacrifices to ancestors and deities to give thanks for the harvest and pray for a prosperous new year. The word "Nian" (<span class="chinese-char">年</span>) originally referred to the ripening of grain &mdash; a full harvest cycle.</p>
      <p>By the Zhou Dynasty, formalised celebrations at year's end included communal feasting and ritual offerings. Emperor Wu of Han's calendar reform in 104 BCE fixed the new year to the first day of the first lunar month, establishing the date that has endured for over two thousand years.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="nian-legend">
      <h2>The Legend of Nian (<span class="chinese-char">年獸</span>)</h2>
      <p>According to folk tradition, the mythical beast Nian (<span class="chinese-char">年獸</span>) would emerge from the sea or mountains on New Year's Eve to devour crops, livestock, and even children. The terrified villagers eventually discovered that the creature feared three things: the colour red, loud noises, and bright fire.</p>
      <p>From this legend spring the quintessential New Year customs: hanging red decorations and couplets, setting off firecrackers and fireworks, and lighting bonfires and lanterns. While the legend's exact origins are debated, it reflects the fundamentally <em>apotropaic</em> (evil-averting) nature of Spring Festival traditions &mdash; the collective effort to drive away misfortune and welcome renewal.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="fifteen-days">
      <h2>The Fifteen Days of Celebration</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>New Year's Eve (<span class="chinese-char">除夕</span>, Chúxī)</strong> &mdash; The most important night. Families gather for the reunion dinner (<span class="chinese-char">年夜飯</span>). Staying up until midnight (<span class="chinese-char">守歲</span>, shǒusuì) is practised to bid farewell to the old year.</li>
        <li><strong>Day 1</strong> &mdash; Firecrackers at dawn. Wearing new clothes. Visiting elders and receiving red envelopes (<span class="chinese-char">紅包</span>). Auspicious greetings exchanged.</li>
        <li><strong>Day 2</strong> &mdash; Married daughters return to their parents' home (<span class="chinese-char">回娘家</span>). Prayers to the God of Wealth.</li>
        <li><strong>Days 3-4</strong> &mdash; Continuing family visits. In some traditions, Day 3 is considered unlucky for visiting to avoid arguments.</li>
        <li><strong>Day 5</strong> &mdash; Welcoming the God of Wealth (<span class="chinese-char">財神</span>, Cáishén). Firecrackers to attract prosperity. Businesses traditionally reopen.</li>
        <li><strong>Days 6-14</strong> &mdash; Temple fairs (<span class="chinese-char">廟會</span>), folk performances, lantern preparation. The festive atmosphere continues with community gatherings.</li>
        <li><strong>Day 15 &mdash; Lantern Festival (<span class="chinese-char">元宵節</span>)</strong> &mdash; The grand finale. Lanterns displayed, lantern riddles (<span class="chinese-char">燈謎</span>) solved. Families eat <em>tangyuan</em> (glutinous rice balls) symbolising togetherness. The first full moon of the new year.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="customs">
      <h2>Traditional Customs (Pre-Qing)</h2>
      <p><strong>Spring Couplets (<span class="chinese-char">春聯</span>)</strong> &mdash; Paired lines of auspicious poetry hung on doorframes. This literary tradition dates to the Five Dynasties period (907-960 CE), when they were carved on peach wood boards before evolving to red paper during the Ming Dynasty.</p>
      <p><strong>Door Gods (<span class="chinese-char">門神</span>)</strong> &mdash; Painted guardian figures on gates, a custom established by the Tang Dynasty. The most famous pair are Qin Shubao and Yuchi Gong, generals of Emperor Taizong.</p>
      <p><strong>Paper Cutting (<span class="chinese-char">剪紙</span>)</strong> &mdash; Intricate red paper designs depicting zodiac animals, flowers, and auspicious characters, displayed on windows to welcome the new year.</p>
      <p><strong>Red Envelopes (<span class="chinese-char">紅包</span>)</strong> &mdash; Containing lucky money (<span class="chinese-char">壓歲錢</span>, yāsuìqián, literally "money to suppress age"), given by elders to children as blessings for the coming year.</p>
      <p><strong>Firecrackers (<span class="chinese-char">鞭炮</span>)</strong> &mdash; Originally bamboo thrown into fires (which cracked loudly when heated), later evolving into gunpowder firecrackers after the Tang Dynasty invention of black powder.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="foods">
      <h2>Festival Foods</h2>
      <p><strong>Dumplings (<span class="chinese-char">餃子</span>)</strong> &mdash; Shaped like ancient gold ingots (<span class="chinese-char">元寶</span>), symbolising wealth. Families wrap them together on New Year's Eve. Dominant in northern China.</p>
      <p><strong>Nian Gao (<span class="chinese-char">年糕</span>)</strong> &mdash; Sticky rice cake. The name is a homophone for "year higher" (<span class="chinese-char">年高</span>), symbolising rising prosperity. Popular in southern and eastern China.</p>
      <p><strong>Fish (<span class="chinese-char">魚</span>)</strong> &mdash; Always served at the reunion dinner. <em>Yú</em> is a homophone of <span class="chinese-char">餘</span> (surplus), representing the wish for abundance.</p>
      <p><strong>Tang Yuan (<span class="chinese-char">湯圓</span>)</strong> &mdash; Glutinous rice balls eaten during the Lantern Festival. Their round shape symbolises family unity and completeness. The name evokes <span class="chinese-char">團圓</span> (tuányuán, reunion).</p>
    </section>

    <section id="performances">
      <h2>Temple Fairs and Performances</h2>
      <p>The <strong>lion dance</strong> and <strong>dragon dance</strong> date to the Han Dynasty. Temple fairs (<span class="chinese-char">廟會</span>) feature folk performances, stilt walking, <em>yangge</em> dancing, and opera. These gatherings served essential social functions in traditional Chinese society, reinforcing community bonds and providing entertainment during the long winter festival.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="lantern-festival">
      <h2>The Lantern Festival (<span class="chinese-char">元宵節</span>)</h2>
      <p>The Lantern Festival on the 15th day marks the first full moon of the new year. Tradition attributes its origins to Han Dynasty Emperor Ming, who ordered lanterns lit in palaces and temples to honour the Buddha. <strong>Lantern riddles</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">燈謎</span>) &mdash; riddles written on lanterns for people to solve &mdash; became a beloved intellectual pastime by the Song Dynasty.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="zodiac-connection">
      <h2>Spring Festival and the Zodiac</h2>
      <p>Each Chinese New Year ushers in a new <a href="/zodiac/">zodiac animal</a>. The incoming animal's personality is believed to colour the character of the entire year. People born in the same animal year enter their <strong>Ben Ming Nian</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">本命年</span>) &mdash; their own zodiac year &mdash; which is traditionally considered a year of challenges requiring special precautions, most notably wearing red undergarments throughout the year.</p>
    </section>
